metadata.name: Point(); Line(); Plane(); #172
metadata.description:
The title of this piece is a reference to Wassily Kandisky's book "Point and Line to Plane" (1926).

Eight points are placed at random positions, assigned a color and direction, and moved, to become lines. These lines are then translated to form planes.

This idea was already formulated by Aristotle: "a line by its motion produces a surface, and a point by its motion a line".

This simple algorithm creates an interesting variety of compositions, all unique and recognizable.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be exported by pressing "s".

PNG exports can be obtained by pressing "1" (3300√ó1900) or "2" (6600√ó3800).

metadata.name: Helio_Motion #93
metadata.description:
Original piece by Ismahelio. p5js.

Infinite combinations of minimal, cubist like, glitch 3d-2dimensional illustrations
There is a huge variation in color combinations, some of them are inspired by digital and physical artists.
Chances to get a specific color palette are:
 
1 % Locomotion
3 % Lionel Radisson
6 % Acidquiat
10 % Saura
10 % Wong
15 % NFT Biker
25 % CMYK
30 % Ganbrood

There's also rarity in the number of shapes and the piece sizes: S, M, L, and XL.

The piece is interactive. Depending on the number of views, the animation will change if you click on the screen. If the number of views is 1, then it won't change!

metadata.name: Miniscapes #199
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Influence #1
metadata.description:
We are all influenced by our context, and this is an artistic interpretation of this concept. The phenomenon of localized influence is most apparent when the animation is enabled (see instructions below). Choose your influences wisely.

Press p to pause and unpause the animation. The animation requires significant computational resources and may not work on under-powered devices.

Press s to export a hi-res png.

metadata.name: WTBS Logo with Friends #159
metadata.description:
Did you know that WTBS is now sixth months old? If we were Will‚Äôs baby, we‚Äôd be sitting up and prepping to crawl ‚Äî the literal baby steps that precede an entire lifetime of movement. 

Play is another integral part of our development. Play teaches us to connect, laugh, share, love, and learn. It helps form our earliest friendships that mold us into who we are destined to become. Over the last six months we have had the immense pleasure of forming new relationships with some of the amazing artists that comprise of the fxhash community. 

It is the love and support of new friends Laurent Houdard, Ada Ada Ada, elsif, and Camille Roux that made our first (official) collaboration possible. Thank you so much for the idea, the vision, the art, the time, and the wrangling to make this possible. 

Each letter is imbued with the unique style of an artist, based on a framework created by Laurent. There is a small chance of receiving a piece with two of the same style, with the rarest possibility of receiving one with all four quadrants the same. 

Collect with love and the knowledge that your support means the world to us. Thank you for listening every week, and for the messages and stories that you share with us. We can‚Äôt wait to continue to grow.

Thank you so much again to Laurent, Ada, elsif, and Camille. This is what community is.

metadata.name: Pobbles #88
metadata.description:
The pobbles are generative blob-rocks: staring in silence, sometimes half-smiling, generally bored. 

‚Ä¢ The pobbles are digital recreations of a series of rock-doodles by S.F.Kislev (my big brother). They are an attempt to capture a specific, singular handwriting, and evolve it using code. 
‚Ä¢ See the original, 2014 handmade version here - https://pobbles.tez.page..
‚Ä¢ Alternative titles considered include Peggles‚Ñ¢, Plops‚Ñ¢, Blobbies‚Ñ¢, Floofs‚Ñ¢, Flintstones‚Ñ¢, Lardies‚Ñ¢, Plumps‚Ñ¢, Fats‚Ñ¢ and Wet-Ones‚Ñ¢. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are written entirely in paper.js and p5.js. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are an effort to take generative art into the realm of the cute. 
‚Ä¢ They work well with toddlers.

metadata.name: Rain Ritual #164
metadata.description:
Every windy gust.... every breeze, gave the restless grasses a chance to spread their suggestive rumours, their spurious gossip. All the while, Old Ones of the field towered above, chanting to their wrathful Sky God for more rain.... Always more rain. 

Instructions 
Intended for high resolutions. Use the following keys once render is complete, to export (letters export without a border) 

Square mode 
   1 (q) : 2048x2048  
   2 (w) : 3072x3072 
   3 (e) : 4096x4096 
   4 (r) : 5120x5120 

Landscape mode (increases spacing between objects to preserve aspect ratio) 
   5 (t) : 2560x1440 
   6 (y) : 3840x2160 
   7 (u) : 5128x2880 
   8 (I) : 7680x4320 

Note: Generated textures are resolution dependant, resulting in very slight differences across resolutions. Composition however, remains identical. 

Browsers 
Tested with Chrome, Edge and Firefox on Windows, Chrome on Mac. 
Note for Firefox users : Ensure "Use hardware acceleration" is ticked ‚Äì Found in Settings / Performance. Other advanced settings to enable include : gfx.canvas.accelerated,  gfx.direct2d.force-enabled and gfx.offscreencanvas.enabled - Unfortunately even with these, Firefox appears slower than other browsers.  

Shoulders of Giants [license text and links included in source] 
- Aristid Lindenmayer ‚Äì Formal L-System language (Tree routine) 
- P5.js - Creative coding framework 
- JS Topology Suite "JSTS", a port of Java Topology Suite "JTS" - High-level Geometry library 

Additional JS functions 
- Epistemex - Cardinal Splines library (Curve calculations) 
- MaetDol - K-Means library (Tree foliage routine) 
- Angelos Chalaris - Directed Graphs Tutorial (Tree routine)

metadata.name: ProcGen Entomology #425
metadata.description:
Realtime 3D in-browser procedural generation of insect-like models, with a look reminiscent of vintage entomology illustrations.

The project is about the fact that insects are cool first and foremost.
This is also about nostalgia.

Everything is procedural except for the font. The exposed features only describe the most visible parts.

I wrote mord words, about where it came from, and some technical details on the procedural aspect at:
https://ulucode.com/projects/entomology/

GPU Required!

Interface : 
Space : show/hide menu
Mouse Left : Rotate
Mouse Right : Pan
Mouse Middle/Wheel : Zoom

Captures only work in Live mode.
